  <section>
    <h2 class="heading-l">Usage examples</h2>
    <p>Apply tokens directly in component transitions and animations:</p>
    <pre><code>/* Button hover — fast, decelerating */
.button {
  transition: background var(--motion-duration-fast) var(--motion-easing-out);
}

/* Dropdown open — standard, decelerating */
.dropdown[open] {
  animation: slide-down var(--motion-duration-base) var(--motion-easing-out) both;
}

/* Modal entrance — slower, decelerating */
.dialog[open] {
  animation: fade-up var(--motion-duration-slow) var(--motion-easing-out) both;
}

/* Modal exit — ease-in so it accelerates away */
.dialog:not([open]) {
  animation: fade-down var(--motion-duration-base) var(--motion-easing-in) both;
}

/* Success badge — spring for playful feedback */
.badge[data-status="ok"] {
  animation: pop-in var(--motion-duration-fast) var(--motion-easing-spring) both;
}</code></pre>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 class="heading-l">Reduced motion</h2>
    <p>All five duration tokens are automatically set to <code>0ms</code> when the user has set their operating system to reduce motion (<code>prefers-reduced-motion: reduce</code>). Because every animation and transition in the library references these tokens, <strong>all motion is disabled globally without any per-component overrides</strong>.</p>
    <pre><code>/* Built into _motion.css — you do not need to write this yourself */
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  :root {
    --motion-duration-instant:    0ms;
    --motion-duration-fast:       0ms;
    --motion-duration-base:       0ms;
    --motion-duration-slow:       0ms;
    --motion-duration-deliberate: 0ms;
  }
}</code></pre>
    <div class="callout" data-variant="brand" role="note"><p>This approach satisfies WCAG 2.1 Success Criterion 2.3.3 (AAA). Any custom animations you add should also reference these tokens rather than hardcoding millisecond values so they benefit from the same override automatically.</p></div>
  </section>

